{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_014ipZZGub7GsqnmNCGxm4LD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The Deployment command is:\n```\nray start --head --node-ip-address=\"${MY_POD_IP}\" --port=6379 --include-dashboard=false --num-cpus=0 --block\n```\n\nThe dashboard is currently running with `--host=127.0.0.1` (localhost-only). I need to:\n1. Change `--include-dashboard=false` to `--dashboard-host=0.0.0.0` \n\nIn Ray 2.9.0, the flag to control dashboard host is `--dashboard-host`. I can add that to make it listen on all interfaces.\nPatching the Deployment would trigger a pod restart, which could be disruptive. I could instead use `kubectl exec` to set up a port redirect inside the pod without restarting, or kill and restart just the dashboard process.\n\nLooking at the actual command running, the dashboard is bound to 127.0.0.1 even though `--include-dashboard=false` is set—Ray 2.9.0 still runs it with `--disable-frontend`. I'll go with killing the dashboard process (PID 153) and restarting it with `--host=0.0.0.0` since that's less risky than patching the Deployment.\n\nBut there's a catch: Ray supervises child processes from the main `ray start` command, so killing the dashboard might just cause Ray to restart it with the same localhost binding. I should check if socat or iptables are available as alternatives, though patching the Deployment would be the cleanest approach even if it requires a pod restart.\n\nActually, I can modify the Deployment to add `--dashboard-host=0.0.0.0` instead of `--include-dashboard=false`, which would bind the dashboard to all interfaces without needing to kill processes. Let me try the socat approach first since it avoids a pod restart and worker reconnection issues.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3760,"cache_read_input_tokens":36406,"cache_creation":{"ephemera